I take a sample and record the gravity each time I rack the mead.
So at the minimum for me, that makes 3 -- original, rack to secondary,
bottling.  But I seem to do at least two rackings on most batches,
probably because of my ale based habit of racking to the secondary
when activity has slowed rather than when it has stopped.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Tasting a young made will only result in the same response of, &quot;Gee,
&gt;this tastes like rocket fuel.&quot;
">

I taste all of the samples (which are about 8 ounces), and all but
the original tend to be sipped and enjoyed over a relaxed span of
time.  It is my as yet unproven theory that I will learn to recognize
the flavor pattern and learn to predict (somewhat) where the flavor
is going.  That (again, I hope) will help me decide whether to oak,
how long, add honey, etc.

I don't find the young mead to taste like rocket fuel, though I am
tasting it with the expectation that it is young and not yet smoothly
blended in its flavors.

Clearly, every 10 mead makers will have at least 12 opinions on the matter.

