Yes, that's something I forgot about in my original
response.  When I make mead with fruit, the primary
fermentation is generally without fruit, and I rack
onto the fruit (cherries, usually), then at a later
date, rack again to get the mead off the fruit and
let particles settle out.  I not only like to taste
the mead straight (before fruit) to see if maybe I
want to hold some unfruited mead back, but to see if
something has gone terribly wrong and I'd just be wasting
the fruit.  Then before racking off the fruit, I want
to see if maybe I want more fruit flavor, in which
case I rack onto more fruit.

So I guess the overall moral of the story is to take
absolute answers in USENET newsgroups (or anywhere) with
a grain of salt-- there's rarely one fixed answer foir
all eventualities.

